  "prompt": "What are the abbreviations for degrees?",
  "response": "The term \"degrees\" can refer to different concepts depending on the context, such as temperature scales, angular measurements, or academic qualifications. Below are the common abbreviations for each type:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Temperature Degrees**\n\n- **Degrees Celsius**\n  - **Abbreviation:** \u00b0C\n  - **Example:** 25\u202f\u00b0C\n\n- **Degrees Fahrenheit**\n  - **Abbreviation:** \u00b0F\n  - **Example:** 77\u202f\u00b0F\n\n- **Degrees Kelvin**\n  - **Abbreviation:** K\n  - **Note:** Kelvin is technically not expressed with the degree symbol.\n  - **Example:** 298\u202fK\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Angular Measurements**\n\n- **Degrees**\n  - **Symbol:** \u00b0\n  - **Example:** 90\u00b0\n\n- **Minutes of Arc**\n  - **Symbol:** \u2032\n  - **Abbreviation:** min\n  - **Example:** 30\u2032\n\n- **Seconds of Arc**\n  - **Symbol:** \u2033\n  - **Abbreviation:** sec\n  - **Example:** 15\u2033\n\n**Combined Example:**\n- 45\u00b0 30\u2032 15\u2033\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Academic Degrees**\n\nAcademic degrees have their own standard abbreviations, typically derived from Latin. Here are some common examples:\n\n- **Associate Degrees**\n  - **Associate of Arts:** AA\n  - **Associate of Science:** AS\n\n- **Bachelor\u2019s Degrees**\n  - **Bachelor of Arts:** BA or B.A.\n  - **Bachelor of Science:** BS or B.S.\n  - **Bachelor of Fine Arts:** BFA\n\n- **Master\u2019s Degrees**\n  - **Master of Arts:** MA or M.A.\n  - **Master of Science:** MS or M.S.\n  - **Master of Business Administration:** MBA\n\n- **Doctoral Degrees**\n  - **Doctor of Philosophy:** Ph.D.\n  - **Doctor of Medicine:** MD\n  - **Doctor of Education:** Ed.D.\n\n- **Professional Degrees**\n  - **Juris Doctor:** JD\n  - **Doctor of Dental Surgery:** DDS\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Miscellaneous Uses**\n\n- **Degree Symbol in General Usage:** \u00b0\n  - Used to denote degrees in various contexts, such as angles, geographic coordinates, and temperature.\n  - **Example in Coordinates:** 40\u00b0 N, 74\u00b0 W\n\n---\n\n**Note on Usage:**\n- When writing temperature, always precede the degree symbol with the number (e.g., 20\u00b0C).\n- In angle measurements, ensure proper spacing and use of symbols (e.g., 180\u00b0).\n- Academic degree abbreviations are typically written after an individual's name or on their credentials (e.g., Jane Doe, Ph.D.).\n\nIf you had a specific type of degree abbreviation in mind, feel free to provide more details!",
